  "prompt": "How do I sync my Gmail contacts?",
  "response": "The process for syncing your Gmail contacts depends on the device or platform you're using. Here's a breakdown for common scenarios:\n\n**1. Android Devices:**\n\n   * **Gmail is already deeply integrated with Android.** Generally, if you've added your Gmail account to your Android device, contacts should sync automatically. Here's how to double-check and troubleshoot:\n\n      * **Check Account Sync Settings:**\n         1.  Go to **Settings** on your Android device.\n         2.  Find **Accounts** (or **Accounts and sync** or something similar). The exact wording varies by Android version.\n         3.  Tap on your **Google** account (the one associated with your Gmail).\n         4.  Make sure the **Contacts** toggle is turned **on** (it should be blue or green).  If it's off, turn it on.\n         5.  Sometimes, you might need to tap the \"Sync account\" option at the bottom and manually trigger a sync.\n\n      * **Check Default Contact Account:**\n         1. Open your **Contacts** app (Google Contacts app is usually pre-installed, but some manufacturers have their own).\n         2.  Go to **Settings** (usually a three-dot menu or gear icon within the app).\n         3.  Look for something like \"**Default account for new contacts**\" or \"**Storage location**\".  Make sure it's set to your **Gmail** account, not \"Phone\" or \"SIM card\".  If it's not, change it to your Gmail account.  This ensures that new contacts you add are saved to your Google account and will sync.\n\n      * **Clear Cache and Data of Contacts App (If Syncing Still Doesn't Work):** This is a more aggressive step, so use it only if other methods fail.\n         1. Go to **Settings** > **Apps** (or **Applications** or **App Manager**).\n         2. Find the **Contacts** app (sometimes listed as \"Contacts Storage\").\n         3. Tap **Storage**.\n         4. Tap **Clear Cache** and then **Clear Data**.  **WARNING:** Clearing data will remove all local copies of your contacts from your phone *temporarily*. They *should* sync back from Google if your account is set up correctly, but back up your contacts before doing this just in case!  You can back up through the Google Contacts website (see below) or by exporting your contacts as a .vcf file.\n         5. Restart your device.\n         6. Check your Google account settings again (as described above) to make sure Contacts sync is enabled.\n\n**2. iPhone/iPad (iOS):**\n\n   * **Add Your Google Account:**\n      1. Open **Settings** on your iPhone or iPad.\n      2. Scroll down and tap **Contacts**.\n      3. Tap **Accounts**.\n      4. Tap **Add Account**.\n      5. Choose **Google**.\n      6. Sign in with your Gmail address and password.\n      7. On the next screen, make sure the **Contacts** toggle is turned **on** (it should be green).\n      8. Tap **Save**.\n\n   * **Set Gmail as the Default Account for Contacts (Recommended):**\n      1. Go to **Settings** > **Contacts** > **Default Account**.\n      2. Choose your **Gmail** account.  This ensures that new contacts you create on your iPhone will be saved to your Google account and synced.\n\n   * **Troubleshooting (if Contacts are not syncing):**\n      1. **Check Internet Connection:** Make sure your iPhone/iPad is connected to Wi-Fi or cellular data.\n      2. **Force a Sync:**  Go to **Settings** > **Contacts** > **Accounts** > **Gmail** and toggle the Contacts switch off and then back on. This can sometimes trigger a resync.\n      3. **Remove and Re-add the Google Account:** Go to **Settings** > **Contacts** > **Accounts** > **Gmail**, tap **Delete Account**, and then re-add it following the steps above.  This is often effective for stubborn syncing issues.\n      4. **Check Background App Refresh:** Go to **Settings** > **General** > **Background App Refresh**. Make sure \"Background App Refresh\" is turned on globally, and that Gmail (or the Contacts app, if it has a separate entry) is also enabled within the list.\n\n**3. Web (Accessing your contacts through a browser on any computer):**\n\n   * **Google Contacts Website:** This is the primary place to manage and view your synced Gmail contacts.\n\n      1. Go to: **contacts.google.com**\n      2. Sign in with your Gmail account.\n      3. You should see all your synced contacts.\n\n   * **Checking Account:**  Make sure you're logged into the correct Google account (the one where you expect your contacts to be).  Sometimes, people have multiple Google accounts and accidentally look in the wrong one.\n\n**Important Notes and Tips:**\n\n* **Contact Conflicts:**  Sometimes, you may have duplicate contacts. Google Contacts has a built-in feature to help find and merge duplicates.  Look for a \"Merge & fix\" option in the left-hand menu of the Google Contacts website.\n* **Groups/Labels:** Contacts are often organized using groups (or labels).  Be sure you're looking in the correct group.\n* **Backup:** It's always a good idea to periodically back up your contacts. In Google Contacts (website), you can export your contacts as a .vcf file (vCard) which you can then store securely.\n* **Storage Limits:** While unlikely, Google accounts do have storage limits. If your Google account is completely full, it might interfere with syncing.  Check your Google Drive storage at drive.google.com.\n* **Contact Formats:** The best practice is to enter contact information in a standardized way (e.g., country code for phone numbers). This helps with correct syncing and recognition.\n* **Third-Party Apps:** If you're using a third-party contacts app, make sure it's configured to sync with your Google account.  The settings for this will vary depending on the app.  If possible, use the Google Contacts app for the best integration.\n* **Sync Frequency:** Syncing doesn't happen instantly. It can take a few minutes (or sometimes a bit longer) for changes to propagate across all your devices.  Forcing a manual sync (as described in the instructions above) can help speed things up.\n\nBy following these steps, you should be able to successfully sync your Gmail contacts across your devices. If you're still having problems, provide more details about your specific situation (device, app, error messages) and I can offer more targeted assistance.\n",
